fully kept during a thirty-four-year marriage. The 188 superbly edited letters gathered here show Samuel Clemens having few idle moments in 1869. When he was not relentlessly "banged about from town to town" on the lecture circuit or busily revising The Innocents Abroad, the book that would make his reputation, he was writing impassioned letters to Olivia. These letters, the longest he ever wrote, make up the bulk of his correspondence for the year and are filled with his acute wit and dazzling language. This latest volume of Mark Twain's Letters captures Clemens on the verge of becoming the celebrity and family man he craved to be. This volume has been supported by the National Endowment for the Humanities and by a major donation to the Friends of The Bancroft Library from the Pareto Fund.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aAmerican literature. 4aEnglish Literature. 4alanguage. 4aliterary collections. 4aliterary studies. 4aliterature. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh1 aArmon, Dahlia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFischer, Victor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrank, Michael B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052090608240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520906082423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520906082/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles